Examples of non-regular sampling distributions

Marshall B.

Tuesday, April 22 2014

  • True Measure Values
  • Evaluate a single risk Model
    • Measures that depend on \(r_H\)
    • Measures that are independ of \(r_H\)

Before we explore areas where inference fails for measures of risk prediction, it is helpful to look at examples where the sampling distribution is non-regular. This document highlights a strange example that shows the non-regularity.

Data is simulated from a linear logistic model with single marker \(Y\). We expect there to be problems for \(HR_D(r_H)\) when \(P(Risk(X_D) = r_H) \neq 0\) (and similarly for \(HR_\bar D (r_H)\)). This motivates the idea to generate \(Y\) from a mixture distribution, where

\(Y \sim N(0 , 1)\) with probability (1- \(rh_{weight}\) ) and

\(Y = y_{r_H}\) with probability \(rh_{weight}\)

The value \(y_{r_H}\) is the value of \(Y\) such that \(Risk(Y) = rh\). Simulations below vary \(rh_{weight}\) from 0 to 0.25.

True Measure Values

For the examples here the marker has very good true performance.

rho HR_D HR_nD NB sNB AUC MRD AARD rh_weight
0.12 0.54 0.26 0.03 0.22 0.7 0.06 0.28 0
0.12 0.51 0.25 0.02 0.2 0.69 0.06 0.28 0.05
0.12 0.48 0.24 0.02 0.19 0.68 0.05 0.26 0.1
0.12 0.38 0.2 0.02 0.15 0.66 0.04 0.23 0.25

Figure 1: distribution of risk given event status. Risk threshold rh shown as a vertical line. rh_weight is shown on the right

Evaluate a single risk Model

Below I show sampling distributions of measure estimates using fitted and true risk scores. 5000 simulationed data sets of sample size 250 were run for each scenario.

Measures that depend on \(r_H\)

1.\(HR_D(r_H) = P(risk(X) > r_H | D = 1)\)

Figure 2: plot of sampling distribution of HR_D(rh) for different values of rh. calculated using 5000 simulations. true values shown by the vertical lines.

2. \(HR_{\bar D}(r_H) = P(risk(X) > r_H | D = 0)\)

Figure 3: plot of sampling distribution of HR_Dbar(rh) for different values of rh_weight. calculated using 5000 simulations. true values shown by the vertical lines.

3. \(NB(r_H) = \rho HR_D(r_H) - (1-\rho)\frac{r_h}{(1-r_H)}HR_{\bar D}(r_H)\)

Figure 4: plot of sampling distribution of NB(rh) for different values of rh_weight. true values shown by the vertical lines.

4. \(sNB(r_H) = HR_D(r_H) - \frac{(1-\rho)}{\rho} \frac{r_h}{(1-r_H)}HR_{\bar D}(r_H)\)

Figure 5: plot of sampling distribution of sNB(rh) for different values of rh_weight. true values shown by the vertical lines.

Measures that are independ of \(r_H\)

Here I include sampling distributions for measures based on fitted risk (conditional estimates) and for measures estimating using risks determined by the true model.

5. \(AUC = Pr(risk(X_i ) \geq risk(X_j ) | D_i = 1, D_j = 0 )\)

Figure 6: plot of sampling distribution of the AUC for different values of rh_weight. true values shown by the vertical lines.

6. \(MRD = E( risk(X) | D = 1) - E( risk(X) | D =0)\)

Figure 7: plot of sampling distribution of the MRD for different values of rh_weight. true values shown by the vertical lines.

7. \(AARD = Pr(risk(X) > \rho | D = 1) - Pr(risk(X) > \rho | D = 0)\)

Figure 8: plot of sampling distribution of the AARD for different values of rh. true values shown by the vertical lines.
